'''Arcadia Biosciences''' ({{nasdaq|RKDA}}) is a publicly-traded American [[agricultural biotechnology]] headquartered in [[Davis, California]] focused on the development of traits to enhance crop quality and productivity.<ref>[https://www.arcadiabio.com/about "Arcadia Biosciences: Company overview"] Retrieved on 9 May 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://macondaily.com/2018/05/04/financial-analysis-arcadia-biosciences-rkda-its-competitors-updated.html|title=Arcadia Biosciences (RKDA) vs. The Competition Head to Head Review|first=Michael|last=Taylor|date=4 May 2018|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> The company is partly owned by [[Moral Compass Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.valuewalk.com/2018/03/arcadia-biosciences-inc-rkda-united-states-steel-corp-x/|title=Arcadia Biosciences, Inc. (RKDA) and United States Steel Corp. (X) Activist Update - ValueWalk|date=10 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>

It has developed a reduced-[[gluten]] and enhanced starch variety of wheat under the name GoodWheat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sacramento/news/2018/04/17/arcadia-announces-reduced-gluten-wheat-for-breads.html  |title= Arcadia announces reduced-gluten wheat for breads, pasta |newspaper=Sacramento Business Journal |first1= Mark |last1=Anderson  |date= April 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sacramento/news/2018/03/21/arcadia-biosciences-goodwheat-product-could-be-on.html  |title=Arcadia Biosciences' GoodWheat product could be on supermarket shelves this year  |first1= Mark |last1=Anderson |date=March 21, 2018|newspaper=Sacramento Business Journal }} </ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sacramento/news/2018/04/06/davis-based-arcadia-biosciences-crosses-the-valley.html|title=Davis-based Arcadia Biosciences crosses the valley of death |newspaper=Sacramento Business Journal  |first1= Mark |last1=Anderson 
|date=April 6, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2018}}
</ref> Arcadia also has a joint venture with Bioceres called Verdeca, which has developed and is commercializing HB4 technology in soybeans that gained FDA approval in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isaaa.org/kc/cropbiotechupdate/article/default.asp?ID=16716|title=Drought Tolerant HB4 Soybeans Introduced in Argentina- Crop Biotech Update {{!}} ISAAA.org/KC|last=|first=|date=|website=www.isaaa.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isaaa.org/gmapprovaldatabase/event/default.asp?EventID=403|title=IND-ØØ41Ø-5 {{!}} GM Approval Database- ISAAA.org|website=www.isaaa.org|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> HB4 soybeans have increased yield up to 30% while being more resistant to abiotic stress such as drought.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://efarmnewsar.com/2018-06-27/bioceres-drought-tolerant-soybean-ready-to-market-in-2019.html|title=Bioceres drought tolerant soybean ready to market in 2019|date=2018-06-27|work=Farm News Argentine|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-US}}</ref>

