'''Hugh Elliott Eaglesham''' (June 3, 1873<ref name="normandin"/> &ndash; October 1938<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ourroots.ca/page.aspx?id=3922497 |title=A tale of two families |pages=97- |year=1982 |last=Eaglesham |first=Isabelle |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref>) was a physician and political figure in [[Saskatchewan]]. He represented [[Weyburn-Big Muddy|Weyburn]] from 1934 to 1938 in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan]] as a [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party|Liberal]].

He was born in [[Clifford, Ontario]], the son of Hugh Eaglesham and Margaret Marshall, and was educated in [[Harriston, Ontario|Harriston]] and at [[University of Toronto Faculty of Medicine|Trinity Medical College]]. In 1896, he married Mary Fletcher. Eaglesham served as president of the Saskatchewan Medical Council and was [[coroner]] for [[Weyburn, Saskatchewan]].<ref name="normandin">{{cite book |title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide |last=Normandin |first=A L |year=1937}}</ref> Eaglesham defeated [[Tommy Douglas]] to win his seat in the provincial assembly in 1934.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lOX4Cal-54EC&pg=PA169 |title=Saskatchewan Premiers of the Twentieth Century |page=169 |last=Barnhart |first=Gordon |ISBN=0889771642 |year=2004 |publisher=Canadian Plains Research Center Press |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref>

